```suggestion
lemma mapsTo_fst_prod {s : Set α} {t : Set β} : MapsTo Prod.fst (s ×ˢ t) s :=
```

```suggestion
lemma mapsTo_snd_prod {s : Set α} {t : Set β} : MapsTo Prod.snd (s ×ˢ t) t :=
```
I wonder if both this one and `snd_image_prod_subset` are really necessary...
In such basic files, I think it's important to have a very thorough API, because it will be used in so many places. So I'd say both are worth keeping.

In that case, maybe the proof of `snd_image_prod_subset` should be golfed with [.image_subset](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Set/Function.html#Set.MapsTo.image_subset)
The proofs of all these lemmas are already one-liners, I'm not sure there's anything to be gained from golfing further.

presumably `t` should be explicit here?
```suggestion
lemma mapsTo_fst_prod {s : Set α} (t : Set β) : MapsTo Prod.fst (s ×ˢ t) s :=
```

I don't think so: in most cases, this should be used to clear side goals where everything is already known, and in the other cases one can use the `(t := foo)` syntax. That's quite different from Lean 3, where it should definitely have been explicit.

```suggestion
lemma mapsTo_snd_prod (s : Set α) {t : Set β} : MapsTo Prod.snd (s ×ˢ t) t :=
```
